  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Facilitation to increase Urban Resilience in Freetown</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Residents of Tower Catchment Area</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sierra Leone is prone to natural disasters, mainly recurrent floods, drought, and landslides, which are likely to be exacerbated by climate change. The core problem is that people living in risk-prone slum communities in Freetown experience frequent recurring climate-induced natural disasters resulting in greater exposure to health risks, loss of life, loss of property and economic instability. Natural disasters, principally floods, are becoming more frequent and have increased in intensity because of increased accumulation of silt and gravel.  The build-up of materials causes increased potential for flooding throughout the watershed, but particularly within informal settlements and slum communities. Environmental degradation, through mangrove destruction, deforestation and sand mining, increases the speed and force of the waterflow and the amount of the silt and gravel moving through the watershed. Inadequate drainage canals and culverts exacerbates the situation. The degradation also exposes the communities in the upper catchments to landslides. Unregulated disposal of solid wastes contributes to the severity and frequency of flooding. Therefore, in that view, Cordaid partner CRS in implementing an urban resilience and Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) project to support the Local government (FCC), local communities and other stakeholders at the Catchment Area scale (in the Tower Hill Catchment Area of Freetown which includes 14 communities with about 284 000 residence, to accelerate community-managed and local Government resilience/ DRM priorities in the target area of operations in Freetown.  This would include joint technical and financial support to establish at least one Resilient Catchment Area Platform. The intervention is focused on mitigation and preparedness in disaster-prone communities&#x2014;those hit cyclically by floods, landslides, and other crises, especially in areas facing the growing effects of climate change.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project intends to increase household community resilience capacity to prevent, withstand, and recover from recurring climate-induced natural disasters, at the community, ward, catchment and city scales in Freetown over 2 years.</narrative>
  </description>
